SIMPLE: ought
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ought
<hw>Ought</hw> <pr>(⟦add⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n. & adv.</pos> <def>See
<er>Aught</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ought</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ought
<hw>Ought</hw>, <pos>imp., p. p., or auxiliary</pos>. <ety>[Orig. the
preterit of the verb <ets>to owe</ets>. OE. <ets>oughte</ets>,
<ets>aughte</ets>, <ets>ahte</ets>, AS. <ets>⟦amac⟧hte</ets>. ⟦root⟧110.
See <er>Owe</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Was or were under obligation
to pay; owed.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This due obedience which they <qex>ought</qex> to the king.</q>
<rj><qau>Tyndale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The love and duty I long have <qex>ought</qex> you.</q>
<rj><qau>Spelman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[He] said . . . you <qex>ought</qex> him a thousand pound.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Owned; possessed.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The knight the which that castle <qex>ought</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be bound in duty or by moral
obligation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We then that are strong <qex>ought</qex> to bear the infirmities
of the weak.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. xv. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be necessary, fit, becoming, or expedient; to
behoove; -- in this sense formerly sometimes used impersonally or
without a subject expressed.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Well <xex>ought</xex> us
work.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To speak of this as it <qex>ought</qex>, would ask a volume.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Ought</qex> not Christ to have suffered these things?</q>
<rj><qau>Luke xxiv. 26.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Ought</xex> is now chiefly employed as an auxiliary
verb, expressing fitness, expediency, propriety, moral obligation, or
the like, in the action or state indicated by the principal
verb.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Ought</er>, <er>Should</er>.</syn> <usage>
Both words imply obligation, but <xex>ought</xex> is the stronger.
<xex>Should</xex> may imply merely an obligation of propriety,
expendiency, etc.; <xex>ought</xex> denotes an obligation of
duty.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Oughtness</ent>⟦br⟧
